# Functions Without Names

An anonymous function (or closure) is a function that has no specified name. It can be assigned to a variable or passed as an argument.

```php
$greet = function($name) {
    echo "Hello, $name";
};

$greet("Alice"); // Hello, Alice
```

Note the semicolon after the closing brace – it's an assignment.

```php
<?php
$multiply = function($a, $b) {
    return $a * $b;
};

echo $multiply(3, 4); // 12

// They can be passed to other functions
$numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4];
$squared = array_map(function($n) {
    return $n * $n;
}, $numbers);

print_r($squared); // [1, 4, 9, 16]
?>
```

# Capturing Variables from Outer Scope

Anonymous functions can inherit variables from the parent scope using the `use` keyword.

```php
$message = "Hello";
$example = function($name) use ($message) {
    echo "$message, $name";
};
$example("World"); // Hello, World
```

This is different from global – it captures the variable at the time the function is defined.

```php
<?php
$factor = 10;
$calculator = function($number) use ($factor) {
    return $number * $factor;
};

echo $calculator(5); // 50

$factor = 20; // doesn't affect the closure because it was captured earlier
echo $calculator(5); // still 50
?>
```

